text: I'll give this film a chance, but I will really be suprised if it turns out being something completely original and well made. The animation looks brilliant, but with quality animation has to come a good, solid storyline. Movies that have these traits just don't seem to happen anymore (or a lot nowadays) with companies that aren't big like Disney or Dreamworks...( Who also, in my opinion, have made some duds in their time). Animated movies these days just seem overloaded with slapstick, fart jokes and consumerism. It really would be nice to see an animated movie, (like the Land Before Time, Brother Bear or Finding Nemo) that focusus on adventure and life lessons, other than all of this useless slaptick comedy just for these companies to make money. So, "The Nut Job", let's see what you've got.

text: Don't judge the movie by its critics. I was avoiding this movie because I heard of the panned ratings but as it played on a cable channel, it turned out to be great. Well I admit it shared some of the plot aspects with Over the Hedge [e.g. storing food for the winter, animals in human territory] but everyone has their own opinions and I find this movie to be good. I give it a B+.  The downs: it failed to connect through its different personalities, the story is a little predictable, the main character is uncredited for his work, some of the jokes are unfunny, an incompetent character takes all of the credit for the main ones work and the lack of the romantic development between the main character and his girl.   The ups: Good animation and visuals, was interesting [for me], has some values [e.g. teamwork, setting aside your own personal agendas for the good of all, friendship, etc], somewhat funny and the voice acting was topnotch.   Also is it just me or the rat greatly resembles Remey from ratatouille?
